1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,320
Hey, welcome to Fascinating Frontiers
Episode 60.

2
00:00:02,600 --> 00:00:04,560
Today is April 30th, 2026.

3
00:00:04,820 --> 00:00:06,960
Let's look at what's new across the
frontiers

4
00:00:06,960 --> 00:00:08,520
of space and science.

5
00:00:08,900 --> 00:00:10,760
A Falcon Heavy is rolling toward the pad

6
00:00:10,760 --> 00:00:12,800
for its first launch in 18 months

7
00:00:12,800 --> 00:00:15,780
while Europe prepares Ariane Six's second
flight

8
00:00:15,780 --> 00:00:16,760
with four boosters.

9
00:00:17,420 --> 00:00:19,940
Space X just completed back-to-back
launches

10
00:00:19,940 --> 00:00:21,920
of a Falcon Heavy and a Falcon 9.

11
00:00:22,580 --> 00:00:24,980
Both side boosters from the heavy came
back to Earth

12
00:00:24,980 --> 00:00:27,480
and landed safely at landing zones 2 and
40.

13
00:00:28,080 --> 00:00:31,140
This marks the vehicle's return after a
year and a half hiatus.

14
00:00:31,580 --> 00:00:33,040
The successful landings prove

15
00:00:33,040 --> 00:00:34,940
that rapid reusability still works

16
00:00:34,940 --> 00:00:36,500
even for these heavy lift missions.

17
00:00:37,120 --> 00:00:38,240
From an engineering perspective,

18
00:00:38,560 --> 00:00:40,800
it is impressive to see the same hardware
fly

19
00:00:40,800 --> 00:00:43,400
again so reliably after that long gap.

20
00:00:44,480 --> 00:00:46,500
The precision required to bring those
boosters

21
00:00:46,500 --> 00:00:48,600
down on target speaks to how mature

22
00:00:48,600 --> 00:00:50,240
the recovery systems have become.

23
00:00:51,180 --> 00:00:52,760
Now while the heavy was making headlines

24
00:00:52,760 --> 00:00:55,300
on the East Coast, another Falcon 9 was
busy

25
00:00:55,300 --> 00:00:58,240
expanding the biggest satellite
constellation on the planet.

26
00:00:58,680 --> 00:01:00,520
A Falcon 9 launched from California

27
00:01:00,520 --> 00:01:02,760
and successfully deployed its full
complement

28
00:01:02,760 --> 00:01:05,420
of 24 Starlink satellites into orbit.

29
00:01:05,820 --> 00:01:08,160
This keeps the constellation growing at a
steady pace.

30
00:01:08,640 --> 00:01:11,820
It also demonstrates the reliability of
the workhorse rocket

31
00:01:11,820 --> 00:01:13,880
on dedicated rideshare class missions.

32
00:01:14,380 --> 00:01:16,960
You can see how space X has turned this
vehicle

33
00:01:16,960 --> 00:01:19,300
into a true utility player that can handle

34
00:01:19,300 --> 00:01:21,940
both crude flights and these smaller
dedicated launches.

35
00:01:22,460 --> 00:01:24,940
Every new batch like this one strengthens
the network

36
00:01:24,940 --> 00:01:27,580
that so many people now rely on for
internet access

37
00:01:27,580 --> 00:01:29,040
from almost anywhere on earth.

38
00:01:29,920 --> 00:01:31,660
Speaking of things headed toward the moon,

39
00:01:31,860 --> 00:01:34,640
one piece of space X hardware has an
unusual destination

40
00:01:34,640 --> 00:01:35,940
coming up in a few months.

41
00:01:36,880 --> 00:01:38,580
You know what is fascinating about this?

42
00:01:38,960 --> 00:01:42,400
An expended Falcon 9 upper stage is now on
a trajectory

43
00:01:42,400 --> 00:01:44,680
that will cause it to strike the moon in
August.

44
00:01:45,220 --> 00:01:46,720
The deliberate crash will happen

45
00:01:46,720 --> 00:01:49,020
at roughly 2.5 kilometers per second.

46
00:01:49,380 --> 00:01:51,460
That impact will release energy equivalent

47
00:01:51,460 --> 00:01:53,620
to a few hundred kilograms of TNT

48
00:01:53,620 --> 00:01:56,140
and send pressure waves rippling through
solid rock.

49
00:01:56,740 --> 00:01:58,620
Size monitors placed by earlier landers

50
00:01:58,620 --> 00:02:01,300
will detect those waves from hundreds of
kilometers away.

51
00:02:01,720 --> 00:02:04,840
Because we know the exact mass, speed and
impact angle,

52
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:07,400
the event becomes a precisely calibrated
probe

53
00:02:07,400 --> 00:02:09,160
of the moon's crust and mantle.

54
00:02:09,660 --> 00:02:12,540
The really wild part is that the moon
rings like a bell

55
00:02:12,540 --> 00:02:15,020
for up to an hour after even a modest
strike.

56
00:02:15,400 --> 00:02:17,800
It reveals layering we still do not fully
understand.

57
00:02:18,260 --> 00:02:21,060
We can watch the flash from orbit measure
the seismic

58
00:02:21,060 --> 00:02:24,060
Coda from the surface and compare both to
computer models.

59
00:02:24,480 --> 00:02:26,960
Yet one specific mystery refuses to yield.

60
00:02:27,780 --> 00:02:31,700
Why do some lunar impact sites show
unexpectedly deep fracturing

61
00:02:31,700 --> 00:02:34,140
while others appear to heal far faster

62
00:02:34,140 --> 00:02:35,700
than rock physics predicts?

63
00:02:36,340 --> 00:02:38,060
That single unanswered detail

64
00:02:38,060 --> 00:02:40,380
sits at the heart of how the moon's
interior

65
00:02:40,380 --> 00:02:42,500
has evolved over billions of years.

66
00:02:43,000 --> 00:02:44,880
From an artificial impact on the moon

67
00:02:44,880 --> 00:02:48,060
to a very real new rocket preparing to
leave Earth Europe

68
00:02:48,060 --> 00:02:50,540
is about to fly its most powerful launcher
again.

69
00:02:51,200 --> 00:02:53,620
Europe's most powerful rocket, Ariane VI,

70
00:02:53,940 --> 00:02:56,900
is set for its second flight with four
solid boosters.

71
00:02:57,340 --> 00:03:01,700
The launch is scheduled between 9.08 a.m.
and 9.57 a.m.

72
00:03:01,860 --> 00:03:04,200
British summertime on April 30th, 2026.

73
00:03:04,960 --> 00:03:07,900
This mission continues the launchers early
operational campaign.

74
00:03:08,120 --> 00:03:10,860
It also expands Europe's independent heavy
lift capability

75
00:03:10,860 --> 00:03:14,540
at a time when reliable access to space
matters more than ever.

76
00:03:14,820 --> 00:03:16,480
Having a homegrown heavy rocket

77
00:03:16,480 --> 00:03:18,060
that can fly on its own schedule

78
00:03:18,060 --> 00:03:19,780
strengthens the continent's position

79
00:03:19,780 --> 00:03:21,900
in the growing international space
economy.

80
00:03:22,340 --> 00:03:24,940
While new rockets grab the spotlight of
veteran astronaut

81
00:03:24,940 --> 00:03:26,460
with a unique medical background

82
00:03:26,460 --> 00:03:28,280
is getting ready for his first trip to
orbit.

83
00:03:29,040 --> 00:03:31,200
A Neil Menon, a former SpaceX flight
surgeon

84
00:03:31,200 --> 00:03:33,580
and member of NASA's 2021 astronaut class

85
00:03:33,580 --> 00:03:35,160
will make his first trip to space.

86
00:03:35,620 --> 00:03:37,780
His mission launches on July 14th.

87
00:03:37,780 --> 00:03:39,820
He will head to the International Space
Station.

88
00:03:40,300 --> 00:03:42,080
His background in aerospace medicine

89
00:03:42,080 --> 00:03:43,940
brings unique operational insight

90
00:03:43,940 --> 00:03:45,760
to long duration expeditions.

91
00:03:46,560 --> 00:03:48,980
Having a doctor astronaut who already
understands

92
00:03:48,980 --> 00:03:51,500
the spacecraft systems from the operator
side

93
00:03:51,500 --> 00:03:54,320
should prove valuable during what could be
an extended stay.

94
00:03:54,920 --> 00:03:57,440
It is always reassuring when the crew
includes someone

95
00:03:57,440 --> 00:03:59,300
who has lived and breathed the medical
side

96
00:03:59,300 --> 00:04:00,840
of human spaceflight for years.

97
00:04:01,360 --> 00:04:03,000
From the human side of spaceflight,

98
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:05,000
let us swing over to what you can actually
see

99
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:06,240
with your own eyes this month.

100
00:04:06,500 --> 00:04:08,960
This month, the big and little dippers are
riding high

101
00:04:08,960 --> 00:04:10,340
in the northern evening sky.

102
00:04:10,660 --> 00:04:12,960
All five bright planets are visible right
now.

103
00:04:12,960 --> 00:04:16,080
The ETA Aquariod meteors from Halle's
comet

104
00:04:16,080 --> 00:04:17,020
are also active.

105
00:04:17,220 --> 00:04:20,480
Sky and telescope has put together a
complete backyard guide

106
00:04:20,480 --> 00:04:22,920
that helps observers make the most of
these sites.

107
00:04:23,540 --> 00:04:25,700
Even if you only have a few minutes after
dark,

108
00:04:25,980 --> 00:04:28,980
you can step outside, spot the dippers,
trace the planets

109
00:04:28,980 --> 00:04:30,660
and maybe catch a meteor or two.

110
00:04:30,860 --> 00:04:33,080
It is a great time to reconnect with the
sky

111
00:04:33,080 --> 00:04:34,660
without any special equipment.

112
00:04:35,020 --> 00:04:37,160
While we are looking up powerful
telescopes

113
00:04:37,160 --> 00:04:39,140
are still revealing distant galaxies.

114
00:04:39,880 --> 00:04:41,540
NASA's Hubble Space Telescope

115
00:04:41,540 --> 00:04:46,040
imaged the luminous barred spiral galaxy
IC 486.

116
00:04:46,320 --> 00:04:49,260
The image was captured on April 13th,
2026.

117
00:04:49,900 --> 00:04:53,060
It reveals the galaxy's soft glow against
the blackness of space.

118
00:04:53,500 --> 00:04:55,700
You can clearly see the graceful spiral
arms

119
00:04:55,700 --> 00:04:57,640
and the stellar populations that trace
them.

120
00:04:57,900 --> 00:04:59,640
It is a classic example of the structures

121
00:04:59,640 --> 00:05:01,400
that build the universe we see today.

122
00:05:02,400 --> 00:05:04,260
Every new Hubble portrait like this one

123
00:05:04,260 --> 00:05:06,240
reminds me how beautiful and orderly

124
00:05:06,240 --> 00:05:09,360
spiral galaxies can look from millions of
light years away.

125
00:05:09,360 --> 00:05:11,840
From galaxies millions of light years
away,

126
00:05:12,040 --> 00:05:13,900
we come back to our own cosmic
neighborhood

127
00:05:13,900 --> 00:05:16,280
and a dramatic event from 1,000 years ago.

128
00:05:16,760 --> 00:05:20,420
On April 30th, 10-6, the brightest
supernova

129
00:05:20,420 --> 00:05:23,960
in recorded human history flared in the
constellation Lupus.

130
00:05:24,300 --> 00:05:26,900
It reached 16 times the brightness of
Venus.

131
00:05:27,560 --> 00:05:29,940
The event was visible across China, Japan,

132
00:05:30,120 --> 00:05:31,000
the Middle East, and Europe.

133
00:05:31,120 --> 00:05:33,300
It was reportedly bright enough to read by
at night.

134
00:05:33,940 --> 00:05:35,940
Some researchers think it may even appear

135
00:05:35,940 --> 00:05:37,340
in North American rock art.

136
00:05:38,020 --> 00:05:41,680
That supernova was a reminder of how
dynamic the cosmos can be

137
00:05:41,680 --> 00:05:44,720
and how profoundly those events must have
affected people

138
00:05:44,720 --> 00:05:47,180
who witnessed them without any modern
context.

139
00:05:47,560 --> 00:05:49,720
While lawmakers debate future rockets,

140
00:05:49,960 --> 00:05:52,240
the current Artemis crew recently received

141
00:05:52,240 --> 00:05:53,800
some high-profile encouragement.

142
00:05:54,180 --> 00:05:57,000
President Trump welcomed the Artemis II
crew to the White House.

143
00:05:57,520 --> 00:06:00,520
The event celebrated the upcoming crewed
lunar fly-by mission.

144
00:06:00,920 --> 00:06:03,520
It underscored continued high-level
political support

145
00:06:03,520 --> 00:06:04,920
for NASA's return to the moon.

146
00:06:04,920 --> 00:06:07,280
Seeing the crew recognized at that level

147
00:06:07,280 --> 00:06:09,600
helps keep public attention focused on the
mission

148
00:06:09,600 --> 00:06:11,740
that will send humans beyond lower orbit

149
00:06:11,740 --> 00:06:13,240
for the first time in decades.

150
00:06:14,060 --> 00:06:15,460
Political support is important,

151
00:06:15,620 --> 00:06:18,180
but so is the technology that will let
future explorers

152
00:06:18,180 --> 00:06:19,560
survive on the lunar surface.

153
00:06:19,820 --> 00:06:22,620
Engineers have created hair-thin nanotube
shielding

154
00:06:22,620 --> 00:06:24,360
that can be 3D printed directly

155
00:06:24,360 --> 00:06:26,580
onto electronics and solar panels.

156
00:06:26,960 --> 00:06:29,120
Picture a fleet of autonomous rovers

157
00:06:29,120 --> 00:06:31,180
trundling across the lunar South Pole,

158
00:06:31,460 --> 00:06:32,720
three kilometers from base

159
00:06:32,720 --> 00:06:35,820
when a solar storm alert suddenly lights
up mission control.

160
00:06:36,360 --> 00:06:38,180
Instead of scrambling to retrieve them,

161
00:06:38,400 --> 00:06:41,040
engineers can simply rely on these
lightweight layers.

162
00:06:41,880 --> 00:06:43,620
The shielding adds almost no mass,

163
00:06:43,880 --> 00:06:45,680
yet it is flexible enough to survive

164
00:06:45,680 --> 00:06:48,600
the extreme temperature swings and
vibration of launch.

165
00:06:49,320 --> 00:06:51,240
Early tests suggest it can deflect

166
00:06:51,240 --> 00:06:53,180
the worst of the high-energy particles

167
00:06:53,180 --> 00:06:55,580
that would otherwise fry unshielded
systems.

168
00:06:56,080 --> 00:06:58,060
What comes next is flight qualification

169
00:06:58,060 --> 00:06:59,600
on actual lunar hardware.

170
00:07:00,240 --> 00:07:02,820
That could open the door to long-duration
robotic missions

171
00:07:02,820 --> 00:07:04,540
in permanently shadowed regions.

172
00:07:04,960 --> 00:07:05,880
One question remains,

173
00:07:06,240 --> 00:07:08,060
how will these nanotube layers hold up

174
00:07:08,060 --> 00:07:10,640
after years of micrometeorite sandblasting

175
00:07:10,640 --> 00:07:13,060
and relentless UV exposure on the moon?

176
00:07:13,620 --> 00:07:14,940
Protecting hardware is one thing.

177
00:07:15,080 --> 00:07:17,480
Sometimes you have to cancel hardware
entirely.

178
00:07:17,840 --> 00:07:20,720
The Canadian Space Agency terminated last
year's contract

179
00:07:20,720 --> 00:07:22,400
with Spire Global to build a fleet

180
00:07:22,400 --> 00:07:25,360
of small satellites dedicated to
monitoring wildfires.

181
00:07:25,960 --> 00:07:28,080
The decision ends one planned contribution

182
00:07:28,080 --> 00:07:30,360
to Canada's Earth observation
capabilities.

183
00:07:30,820 --> 00:07:32,660
It is never easy to cancel a project,

184
00:07:32,740 --> 00:07:34,180
especially one aimed at something

185
00:07:34,180 --> 00:07:35,900
as important as wildfire tracking.

186
00:07:36,440 --> 00:07:38,240
Still, these kinds of adjustments happen

187
00:07:38,240 --> 00:07:39,880
as budgets and priorities shift

188
00:07:39,880 --> 00:07:41,680
across government space programs.

189
00:07:42,460 --> 00:07:44,740
On a brighter note, new materials and
clever ideas

190
00:07:44,740 --> 00:07:46,280
are still moving forward at NASA.

191
00:07:46,840 --> 00:07:48,620
Al Nash from the Jet Propulsion Laboratory

192
00:07:48,620 --> 00:07:50,740
spoke on moving interesting ideas

193
00:07:50,740 --> 00:07:52,520
to selected astra studies.

194
00:07:52,980 --> 00:07:55,420
The seminar took place on April 30th.

195
00:07:55,420 --> 00:07:56,680
It explored considerations

196
00:07:56,680 --> 00:08:00,380
for advancing early stage astrophysics
technology concepts.

197
00:08:00,740 --> 00:08:03,900
Hearing how JPL thinks about turning
promising ideas

198
00:08:03,900 --> 00:08:05,900
into funded studies gives a glimpse

199
00:08:05,900 --> 00:08:07,780
into the careful filtering process

200
00:08:07,780 --> 00:08:09,240
that shapes future missions.

201
00:08:09,800 --> 00:08:11,800
While we push new tech Earth itself,

202
00:08:12,280 --> 00:08:13,360
keeps putting on quite a show.

203
00:08:14,420 --> 00:08:15,700
As winter gave way to spring,

204
00:08:16,100 --> 00:08:18,660
distinct cloud patterns formed textbook
examples

205
00:08:18,660 --> 00:08:21,900
of various atmospheric phenomena over the
Gulf of Alaska.

206
00:08:22,720 --> 00:08:24,780
Satellite imagery captured the transition

207
00:08:24,780 --> 00:08:27,340
and the dynamic weather system shaping
Earth's

208
00:08:27,340 --> 00:08:28,400
high latitude skies.

209
00:08:28,960 --> 00:08:31,640
The images are a beautiful reminder that
even from orbit,

210
00:08:31,840 --> 00:08:33,480
our own planet can look every bit

211
00:08:33,480 --> 00:08:35,720
as dramatic as anything we see in deep
space.

212
00:08:36,420 --> 00:08:39,860
Before we go, keep an eye on how that
upcoming lunar impact

213
00:08:39,860 --> 00:08:43,120
in August unfolds, because the seismic
data could reshape

214
00:08:43,120 --> 00:08:45,340
what we think we know about the Moon's
interior.

215
00:08:45,600 --> 00:08:48,180
That covers today's space and science
news.

216
